d.” Describing the book’s formal qualities and careful structure, Jacobs shows why The Shield of Achilles should be seen as one of Auden’s most central poetic statements—a richly imaginative, beautifully envisioned account of what it means to live, as human beings do, simultaneously in nature and in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnglish poetryy20th century. 7aPOETRY / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAchilles.  aAdam.  aAmphion.  aArcadian.  aArthur.  aBarcarolle.  aBerg Collection.  aBower.  aBrahma.  aBucolics.  aCaedmon.  aCaesar.  aCatholic.  aChrist.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aCivility.  aClio.  aCosimo.  aEden.  aEncounter.  aEpitaph.  aFleet Visit.  aFortunatus.  aGenesis.  aGreek.  aHarry Ransom Center.  aHebrews.  aHephaestos.  aHephaestus.  aHomer.  aHomo Ludens.  aHorae Canonicae.  aHunting Season.  aHuppim.  aIschia.  aJesus.  aKierkegaard.  aKingdom.  aLIB.  aLatin.  aLauds.  aLimestone.  aMemoriam.  aMount Olympus.  aMuppim.  aNew Jerusalem.  aNicaea.  aNones.  aOde to Gaea.  aOxford English Dictionary.  aPamina.  aPangur.  aParadise.  aPiero.  aPoetry.  aPraise.  aRevolution.  aRoman.  aSanguine Thought.  aSappho.  aSext.  aShield.  aTamino.  aTerce.  aThetis.  aTiberius.  aUnknown Soldier.  aUtopian.  aVespers.1 aJacobs, Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691256580?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691256580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691256580/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton Univer